class:: VogueLadderCh
summary:: BYOD ladder filter port with cascaded high-pass, low-pass, and drive
categories:: UGens>Filters
related:: Guides/ChowDSPPorts

Description::

VogueLadderCh follows the public BYOD ladder filter module. The structure is unusual but direct: a resonant four-pole high-pass ladder feeds a resonant four-pole low-pass ladder, and the output then passes through the original nonlinear drive stage. Cutoff is mapped through the same control-voltage-to-frequency law as BYOD, resonance is skew-mapped into the ladder feedback amount, and the drive control crossfades between linear throughput and tanh-style saturation after gain scaling.

A transistor-ladder family filter is historically associated with rounded but forceful subtractive sweeps, especially when resonance is pushed toward self-oscillation. Because this module cascades high-pass and low-pass ladders, it can act like a broad band-pass contour, a resonant sculpting tool, or a self-oscillating synthetic voice element depending on the two cutoff points and resonance settings.

definitionlist::
## hpCutoff: || normalized `0..1`, mapped through the original `-5V..+5V` control-voltage response
## hpResonance: || normalized `0..1`, skewed and mapped to `0..4`
## lpCutoff: || normalized `0..1`, mapped through the original `-5V..+5V` control-voltage response
## lpResonance: || normalized `0..1`, skewed and mapped to `0..4`
## drive: || normalized `0..1`, mapped to `-24..+24 dB` and used both as gain and saturation blend
## oscillating: || `0` keeps resonance capped below self-oscillation, `1` allows full resonance
::

classmethods::

method::ar

argument::in
Input signal.

argument::hpCutoff
Normalized high-pass cutoff.

argument::hpResonance
Normalized high-pass resonance.

argument::lpCutoff
Normalized low-pass cutoff.

argument::lpResonance
Normalized low-pass resonance.

argument::drive
Normalized drive amount.

argument::oscillating
Oscillation mode switch. Values `>= 0.5` enable the uncapped resonance range.

argument::stereo
Set to a positive value to request a 2-channel output. The current implementation processes both channels from the same mono input signal.

argument::mul
Output multiplier.

argument::add
Output offset.


